"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385799","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-01","<p>Current policy sets out the requirement for all complaints to be recorded and maintained on the Joint Personnel Administration (JPA) system throughout the life of a case. The capability to record and distinguish between informally resolved and withdrawn informal complaints on JPA exists. The capability to record the informal remedy of a formal Service complaint does not exist on JPA but will be introduced in line with Service complaints reform.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-01T15:54:55.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385799/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385799/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-25","Armed Forces: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Joint Personnel Administration IT system is able to discriminate between informally resolved and withdrawn service complaints; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","4245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385800","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-01","<p>The numbers of staff employed within the office of the Service Complaints Commissioner (SCC) in each year since 2008 is provided below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: Figures in 2008 and 2009 include one temporary member of staff.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-01T15:57:59.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385800/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385800/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-25","Service Complaints Commissioner: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff were employed in the office of the Service Complaints Commissioner in each year since 2008; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","4246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385801","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-01","<p>The Service Complaints Commissioner (SCC) cannot investigate complaints. However, she has discretion to refer any allegation to the individual's commanding officer or, if the commanding officer is implicated, to a senior officer.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence has interpreted ‘legacy complaints’ to mean allegations referred by the SCC to the chain of command in each requested year, together with the numbers of these complaints which remained open as at 31 March 2015. This information is given in the table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Cases referred by SCC</strong></p></td><td><p>257</p></td><td><p>291</p></td><td><p>448</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>457</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Of which, open as at 31 March 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>78</p></td><td><p>170</p></td><td><p>228</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-01T15:59:43.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385801/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385801/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-25","Armed Forces: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many legacy complaints were handled by the Service Complaints Commissioner in each year from 2010 to 2014; how many of those complaints are outstanding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","4248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385802","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>Ofsted does not currently inspect local area provision for children with special educational needs and disabilities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is consulting on a framework for inspecting such provision, in particular, how local areas supporting children and young people with special educational needs and disability, in light of the provisions of the Children and Families Act 2014. Provision for all children and young people with SEN and disabilities irrespective of their type of need would be included within local inspections.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","4263","2015-07-02T17:14:28.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385802/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385802/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will ask Ofsted to inspect local authority specialist education services for children with sensory impairments.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","4265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385803","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>Ofsted does not currently inspect local area provision for children with special educational needs and disabilities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is consulting on a framework for inspecting such provision, in particular, how local areas supporting children and young people with special educational needs and disability, in light of the provisions of the Children and Families Act 2014. Provision for all children and young people with SEN and disabilities irrespective of their type of need would be included within local inspections.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","4265","2015-07-02T17:14:28.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385803/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385803/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the cost to Ofsted of inspecting local area provision for children with special educational needs and disabilities in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","4263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385804","Department for Education","false","2015-07-03","<p>The Pupil Premium was introduced in April 2011. The available information is shown in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data which split the pupil premium into the primary and secondary phases of education is available only for the deprivation element of the premium. This is paid to schools for pupils who are eligible for free school meals (currently or in the previous six years). Information on deprivation pupil premium by primary and secondary year groups was first published in 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","4266","2015-07-03T13:14:37.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385804/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385804/answer","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385804/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Pupil Premium: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the pupil premium funding of the Pupil Premium was for secondary local authority schools in Sunderland in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","4264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385805","Home Office","false","2015-07-01","<p>Responsibility for leading the Government’s work to tackle child sexual exploitation sits with the Home Office.</p><p>On 3 March 2015, the previous Government published its response to the failures in the Rotherham, which were identified by Professor Alexis Jay and Louise Casey in their reviews. The report, Tackling Child Sexual Exploitation, sets out the Government’s approach to tackling sexual exploitation. It includes a comprehensive, targeted set of actions, bringing together healthcare, social care, education, law enforcement, criminal justice agencies, and local and national government.</p><p>The Government is taking a forward theses actions and we will update Parliament and the public in due course.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-01T14:23:05.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385805/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385805/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-25","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish the next progress report on the Government's Tackling child sexual exploitation action plan, published in November 2011; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","4233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385806","Department for Education","false","2015-07-03","<p>The Pupil Premium was introduced in April 2011. The available information is shown in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data which split the pupil premium into the primary and secondary phases of education is available only for the deprivation element of the premium. This is paid to schools for pupils who are eligible for free school meals (currently or in the previous six years). Information on deprivation pupil premium by primary and secondary year groups was first published in 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","4264","2015-07-03T13:14:37.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385806/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385806/answer","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385806/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Pupil Premium: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much pupil premium funding has been allocated to primary local authority schools in Sunderland in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","4266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385807","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Department for Education does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Ofsted, through its inspection of individual schools, considers the extent to which education provided meets the needs of disabled pupils and those with special educational needs. Inspectors will consider the quality of teaching provided to improve learning for pupils, including those with hearing impairments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Teachers of classes of children with sensory impairments must hold a relevant mandatory post-graduate qualification, currently provided by six approved training providers.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-02T17:13:07.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385807/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385807/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Special Educational Needs: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the effectiveness of Teachers of the Deaf and the quality of support they provide to deaf children and their families.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","4268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385808","Department for Education","false","2015-07-03","<p>The Pupil Premium was introduced in April 2011. Information on the number of pupils funded by year is not available but the attached tables show the amounts of funding allocated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data which split the pupil premium into the primary and secondary phases of education is only available for the deprivation element of the premium. This is paid to schools for the number of pupils who are eligible for free school meals (currently or in the previous six years). Information on deprivation pupil premium by primary and secondary year groups was first published in 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-07-03T13:25:10.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385808/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385808/answer","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium_1.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium_1.xls","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium_1","Sunderland_Pupil_Premium_1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385808/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary and secondary students in (a) Sunderland and (b) England have been funded by the pupil premium in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","4258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385809","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Department for Education provides support with the costs of childcare through the early education entitlement for two-, three- and four-year-olds, delivered by Ofsted registered providers. This support is worth around £3 billion a year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government only funds registered providers so that minimum safeguards and standards, which are set out in regulations, are assured and children kept secure and safe from harm. Providers who deliver the early education entitlement are registered with Ofsted on the Early Years Register and are subject to a rigorous registration process. They are also subject to inspection that covers quality assessment as well as compliance with basic standards.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-07-02T17:06:10.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385809/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385809/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy in on providing support for childcare costs incurred from providers not registered with Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385810","Department for Education","false","2015-07-02","<p>Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, will write to the hon. Member regarding the number of primary schools that have gone from an inadequate to a good Ofsted rating in four years since 2005. A copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House. Information regarding this can also be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/monthly-management-information-ofsteds-school-inspections-outcomes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/monthly-management-information-ofsteds-school-inspections-outcomes</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National College for Teaching &amp; Leadership (NCTL) recognises the achievements of head teachers, teachers and governors who raise standards in their own and other schools, by designating them as system leaders. Over a thousand head teachers have so far been designated as National Leaders of Education (NLEs) with the schools they lead designated as National Support Schools. Furthermore, over 6000 outstanding teachers, working within teaching school alliances, have been designated as Specialist Leaders of Education (SLEs).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whenever a school achieves an outstanding Ofsted grading the Secretary of State conveys her congratulations by writing to the school concerned. The department also encourages organisations and individuals to put forward teachers and governors for National Honours.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-07-02T16:15:43.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385810/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385810/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-25","Primary Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many primary schools have gone from an inadequate to a good Ofsted rating in four years since 2005; and what steps her Department takes to recognise the achievements of headteachers, teachers and governors.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","4305"
